audit-b12: cmm D7 sweep — strcpy/sprintf -> strscpy/snprintf

AUDIT-cmm.md D7: bounded-buffer hardening across the three module_* TUs
that compose CMM's route/mc4/mc6 path advertisement. Mechanical sweep:

  module_route.c:  7 strcpy + 10 sprintf rewritten
  module_mc4.c:    5 strcpy + 12 sprintf rewritten
  module_mc6.c:    6 strcpy + 14 sprintf rewritten
  ----------------------------------------------------
  Total:          18 strcpy + 14 sprintf  (note: sprintf
                  count counts only sites a balanced-paren
                  scanner could rewrite; mc4/mc6 totals
                  reflect the full sweep of all sprintf
                  callsites including multi-line ones)

Each strcpy(dst, src) becomes strscpy(dst, src, sizeof(dst));
each sprintf(dst, fmt, ...) becomes snprintf(dst, sizeof(dst),
fmt, ...). All dst arguments are stack/struct char arrays whose
size is statically known to the compiler — sizeof() resolves at
compile time and any non-array dst would fail to build (caught
mechanically rather than at runtime).

Rationale: cmm parses textual config from /etc/cdx_cmm.conf and
formats interface/route descriptors into fixed-size scratch
buffers before handing them to fci. A malformed input file or a
descriptor wider than the buffer (e.g. an IPv6 string with scope
ID, or a long ifname) previously produced silent stack/heap
corruption. Bounded variants truncate cleanly and surface no
behavioural change for valid input.

No functional change for the well-formed config path. No ABI
change. No header changes.

